<p>Block copolymers, in which two dissimilar polymers are covalently joined together, can be designed to form micelles in solution and can be used as self-assembling injectable gels for tissue engineering or wound healing. One challenge is to find ways to create asymmetrical structures, because normally, block addition would occur at both ends of the polymer chain. <bold>Rupar <italic>et al.</italic></bold> (p. <related-article related-article-type="in-this-issue" vol="337" page="559">559</related-article>; see the Perspective by <bold><related-article related-article-type="in-this-issue" vol="337" page="530" issue="6094">Pochan</related-article></bold>) devised a route to link together three diblock copolymers with a capping approach. Protecting one end during growth gave rise to asymmetrical structures.</p>
